trans-unit.source: The **Microsoft Azure Machine Learning Algorithm Cheat Sheet** helps you choose the right machine learning algorithm for your predictive analytics solutions from the Microsoft Azure Machine Learning library of algorithms.
trans-unit.target: The **Microsoft Azure Machine Learning Algorithm Cheat Sheet** helps you choose the right machine learning algorithm for your predictive analytics solutions from the Microsoft Azure Machine Learning library of algorithms.

trans-unit.source: [Azure Machine Learning Studio](https://studio.azureml.net/) comes with a large number of machine learning algorithms for your predictive analytics solutions.
trans-unit.target: [Azure Machine Learning Studio](https://studio.azureml.net/) comes with a large number of machine learning algorithms for your predictive analytics solutions.

trans-unit.source: These algorithms fall into the general machine learning categories of ***regression***, ***classification***, ***clustering***, and ***anomaly detection***, and each one is designed to address a different type of machine learning problem.
trans-unit.target: These algorithms fall into the general machine learning categories of ***regression***, ***classification***, ***clustering***, and ***anomaly detection***, and each one is designed to address a different type of machine learning problem.

trans-unit.source: Notes and terminology definitions for the machine learning algorithm cheat sheet
trans-unit.target: Notes and terminology definitions for the machine learning algorithm cheat sheet

trans-unit.source: The suggestions offered in this algorithm cheat sheet are approximate rules-of-thumb.
trans-unit.target: The suggestions offered in this algorithm cheat sheet are approximate rules-of-thumb.

trans-unit.source: Some can be bent, and some can be flagrantly violated.
trans-unit.target: Some can be bent, and some can be flagrantly violated.

trans-unit.source: This is intended to suggest a starting point.
trans-unit.target: This is intended to suggest a starting point.

trans-unit.source: Don’t be afraid run a head-to-head competition between several algorithms on your data.
trans-unit.target: Don’t be afraid run a head-to-head competition between several algorithms on your data.

trans-unit.source: There is simply no substitute for understanding the principles of each algorithm and understanding the system that generated your data.
trans-unit.target: There is simply no substitute for understanding the principles of each algorithm and understanding the system that generated your data.

trans-unit.source: Every machine learning algorithm has its own style or *inductive bias*.
trans-unit.target: Every machine learning algorithm has its own style or *inductive bias*.

trans-unit.source: For a specific problem, several algorithms may be appropriate and one algorithm may be a better fit than others.
trans-unit.target: For a specific problem, several algorithms may be appropriate and one algorithm may be a better fit than others.

trans-unit.source: But knowing which will be the best fit beforehand is not always possible.
trans-unit.target: But knowing which will be the best fit beforehand is not always possible.

trans-unit.source: In cases like these, several algorithms are listed together in the cheat sheet.
trans-unit.target: In cases like these, several algorithms are listed together in the cheat sheet.

trans-unit.source: An appropriate strategy would be to try one algorithm, and if the results are not yet satisfactory, try the others.
trans-unit.target: An appropriate strategy would be to try one algorithm, and if the results are not yet satisfactory, try the others.

trans-unit.source: Here’s an example from the [Cortana Analytics Gallery](http://gallery.azureml.net/) of an experiment that tries several algorithms against the same data and compares the results: [Compare Multi-class Classifiers: Letter recognition](http://gallery.azureml.net/Details/a635502fc98b402a890efe21cec65b92).
trans-unit.target: Here’s an example from the [Cortana Analytics Gallery](http://gallery.azureml.net/) of an experiment that tries several algorithms against the same data and compares the results: [Compare Multi-class Classifiers: Letter recognition](http://gallery.azureml.net/Details/a635502fc98b402a890efe21cec65b92).

trans-unit.source: There are three main categories of machine learning: **supervised learning**, **unsupervised learning**, and **reinforcement learning**.
trans-unit.target: There are three main categories of machine learning: **supervised learning**, **unsupervised learning**, and **reinforcement learning**.

trans-unit.source: In **supervised learning**, each data point is labeled or associated with a category or value of interest.
trans-unit.target: In **supervised learning**, each data point is labeled or associated with a category or value of interest.

trans-unit.source: An example of a categorical label is assigning an image as either a ‘cat’ or a ‘dog’.
trans-unit.target: An example of a categorical label is assigning an image as either a ‘cat’ or a ‘dog’.

trans-unit.source: An example of a value label is the sale price associated with a used car.
trans-unit.target: An example of a value label is the sale price associated with a used car.

trans-unit.source: The goal of supervised learning is to study many labeled examples like these, and then to be able to make predictions about future data points - for example, to identify new photos with the correct animal or to assign accurate sale prices to other used cars.
trans-unit.target: The goal of supervised learning is to study many labeled examples like these, and then to be able to make predictions about future data points - for example, to identify new photos with the correct animal or to assign accurate sale prices to other used cars.

trans-unit.source: This is a popular and useful type of machine learning.
trans-unit.target: This is a popular and useful type of machine learning.

trans-unit.source: All of the modules in Azure Machine Learning are supervised learning algorithms except for [K-Means Clustering][k-means-clustering].
trans-unit.target: All of the modules in Azure Machine Learning are supervised learning algorithms except for [K-Means Clustering][k-means-clustering].

trans-unit.source: In **unsupervised learning**, data points have no labels associated with them.
trans-unit.target: In **unsupervised learning**, data points have no labels associated with them.

trans-unit.source: Instead, the goal of an unsupervised learning algorithm is to organize the data in some way or to describe its structure.
trans-unit.target: Instead, the goal of an unsupervised learning algorithm is to organize the data in some way or to describe its structure.

trans-unit.source: This can mean grouping it into clusters, as K-means does, or finding different ways of looking at complex data so that it appears simpler.
trans-unit.target: This can mean grouping it into clusters, as K-means does, or finding different ways of looking at complex data so that it appears simpler.

trans-unit.source: In **reinforcement learning**, the algorithm gets to choose an action in response to each data point.
trans-unit.target: In **reinforcement learning**, the algorithm gets to choose an action in response to each data point.

trans-unit.source: It is a common approach in robotics, where the set of sensor readings at one point in time is a data point, and the algorithm must choose the robot’s next action.
trans-unit.target: It is a common approach in robotics, where the set of sensor readings at one point in time is a data point, and the algorithm must choose the robot’s next action.

trans-unit.source: It's also a natural fit for Internet of Things applications.
trans-unit.target: It's also a natural fit for Internet of Things applications.

trans-unit.source: The learning algorithm also receives a reward signal a short time later, indicating how good the decision was.
trans-unit.target: The learning algorithm also receives a reward signal a short time later, indicating how good the decision was.

trans-unit.source: Based on this, the algorithm modifies its strategy in order to achieve the highest reward.
trans-unit.target: Based on this, the algorithm modifies its strategy in order to achieve the highest reward.

trans-unit.source: Currently there are no reinforcement learning algorithm modules in Azure ML.
trans-unit.target: Currently there are no reinforcement learning algorithm modules in Azure ML.

trans-unit.source: **Bayesian methods** make the assumption of statistically independent data points.
trans-unit.target: **Bayesian methods** make the assumption of statistically independent data points.

trans-unit.source: This means that the unmodeled variability in one data point is uncorrelated with others, that is, it can’t be predicted.
trans-unit.target: This means that the unmodeled variability in one data point is uncorrelated with others, that is, it can’t be predicted.

trans-unit.source: For example, if the data being recorded is the number of minutes until the next subway train arrives, two measurements taken a day apart are statistically independent.
trans-unit.target: For example, if the data being recorded is the number of minutes until the next subway train arrives, two measurements taken a day apart are statistically independent.

trans-unit.source: However, two measurements taken a minute apart are not statistically independent - the value of one is highly predictive of the value of the other.
trans-unit.target: However, two measurements taken a minute apart are not statistically independent - the value of one is highly predictive of the value of the other.

trans-unit.source: **Boosted decision tree regression** takes advantage of feature overlap or interaction among features.
trans-unit.target: **Boosted decision tree regression** takes advantage of feature overlap or interaction among features.

trans-unit.source: That means that, in any given data point, the value of one feature is somewhat predictive of the value of another.
trans-unit.target: That means that, in any given data point, the value of one feature is somewhat predictive of the value of another.

trans-unit.source: For example, in daily high/low temperature data, knowing the low temperature for the day allows you to make a reasonable guess at the high.
trans-unit.target: For example, in daily high/low temperature data, knowing the low temperature for the day allows you to make a reasonable guess at the high.

trans-unit.source: The information contained in the two features is somewhat redundant.
trans-unit.target: The information contained in the two features is somewhat redundant.

trans-unit.source: Classifying data into more than two categories can be done by either using an inherently multi-class classifier, or by combining a set of two-class classifiers into an **ensemble**.
trans-unit.target: Classifying data into more than two categories can be done by either using an inherently multi-class classifier, or by combining a set of two-class classifiers into an **ensemble**.

trans-unit.source: In the ensemble approach, there is a separate two-class classifier for each class - each one separates the data into two categories: “this class” and “not this class.”
trans-unit.target: In the ensemble approach, there is a separate two-class classifier for each class - each one separates the data into two categories: “this class” and “not this class.”

trans-unit.source: Then these classifiers vote on the correct assignment of the data point.
trans-unit.target: Then these classifiers vote on the correct assignment of the data point.

trans-unit.source: This is the operational principle behind [One-vs-All Multiclass][one-vs-all-multiclass].
trans-unit.target: This is the operational principle behind [One-vs-All Multiclass][one-vs-all-multiclass].

trans-unit.source: Several methods, including logistic regression and the Bayes point machine, assume **linear class boundaries**, that is, that the boundaries between classes are approximately straight lines (or hyperplanes in the more general case).
trans-unit.target: Several methods, including logistic regression and the Bayes point machine, assume **linear class boundaries**, that is, that the boundaries between classes are approximately straight lines (or hyperplanes in the more general case).

trans-unit.source: Often this is a characteristic of the data that you don’t know until after you’ve tried to separate it, but it’s something that typically can be learned by visualizing beforehand.
trans-unit.target: Often this is a characteristic of the data that you don’t know until after you’ve tried to separate it, but it’s something that typically can be learned by visualizing beforehand.

trans-unit.source: If the class boundaries look very irregular, stick with decision trees, decision jungles, support vector machines, or neural networks.
trans-unit.target: If the class boundaries look very irregular, stick with decision trees, decision jungles, support vector machines, or neural networks.

trans-unit.source: Neural networks can be used with categorical variables by creating a **dummy variable** for each category and setting it to 1 in cases where the category applies, 0 where it doesn’t.
trans-unit.target: Neural networks can be used with categorical variables by creating a **dummy variable** for each category and setting it to 1 in cases where the category applies, 0 where it doesn’t.
